FISM is a state-of-the-art model-based recommender system proposed by Kabbur et al [9]. This method learns a low rank factorization of an item-item similarity matrix, which is later used to compute the scores to make the predictions. This method is an evolution of a previous method, SLIM [16], that learns this matrix without factorizing it. Factorizing the similarity matrix allows FISM to overcome SLIM’s limitation of not being able to learn a similarity other than zero for items that have never been rated both by at least one user. As a side effect of this factorization, it lowers the space complexity from \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
